President Uhuru Kenyatta yesterday once again reached out to NASA chief Raila Odinga and warned police against using excessive force against demonstrators.Speaking at Harambee House yesterday, the President said he is ready to work with the opposition, adding that his government will bring together all Kenyans irrespective of their political affiliation.&ldquo;We also continue to appeal to the opposition and their supporters that we have extended our hand of peace and friendship for them to use legal mechanisms to express their dissatisfaction,&rdquo; Uhuru said.Uhuru warned the police against using excessive force. He asked them to follow the law and observe professional ethics while dealing with protestors.&ldquo;As a government, we will not allow looting and destruction of property. We ask the police to refrain from using excessive force but to protect life and property,&rdquo; Uhuru added.The President said the General Election is over and the opposition chiefs should avoid streets protests..&ldquo;I appeal to those who have rejected the outcome of the election to go to court. We are all Kenyans. We don&rsquo;t need to fight and take lives,&rdquo; Uhuru said.He told NASA supporters to seek a permit from the police before deemonstrating.&ldquo;If you want to demonstrate don&rsquo;t come to me or to Jubilee. Follow the law and get a permit so that you can demonstrate peacefully. The police are willing and ready to protect you,&rdquo; said Uhuru.On Sunday, Raila said he will not allow Uhuru to get away with &ldquo;another stolen victory&rdquo;, giving the clearest indication that he won&rsquo;t concede defeat.Addressing charged rallies in Kibera and Mathare, the NASA leader said Uhuru, who was declared the winner on Friday night &ldquo;must go&rdquo;.&ldquo;It won&rsquo;t be possible for Uhuru to steal our victory again. It won&rsquo;t happen and we won&rsquo;t allow him to do that,&rdquo; Raila said.He visited the densely populated areas following post-election protests that have resulted in deaths, massive injuries and the loss of property.